{"type":"message","id":"201b6b8c","parentId":"e8d80b61","timestamp":"2026-06-17T16:01:51.328Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_8d36d089d19946dc8f6ba19c","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"searchQueries\": [\n    \"JavaScript TypeScript AI libraries frameworks 2026 developer tools frontend AI integration tutorials React Vue\"\n  ],\n  \"provider\": \"parallel-free\",\n  \"count\": 5,\n  \"tookMs\": 1938,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"parallel-free\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"de82ee8c496f26f1\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nTop JavaScript/TypeScript Gen AI Frameworks for 2026: A Hands-On Comparison | Xavier Portilla Edo\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"de82ee8c496f26f1\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://xavidop.me/genkit/2026-04-16-top-jsts-genai-frameworks-2026\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"103d77739048f6db\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nJump to:\\n\\nNavigation\\n\\n* home\\n* / genkit\\n* / 2026-04-16-top-jsts-genai-frameworks-2026\\n\\n# Top JavaScript/TypeScript Gen AI Frameworks for 2026: A Hands-On Comparison\\n\\n16 Apr 2026 in Genkit on Genkit Last modified at: 2026-05-06\\n\\nTop JavaScript/TypeScript Gen AI Frameworks for 2026: A Hands-On Comparison\\n\\nA practical, in-depth comparison of the top Generative AI frameworks in 2026: Genkit, Vercel AI SDK, Mastra, LangChain, and Google ADK, from someone who has built with all of them. (English)\\n\\n1. Introduction\\n2. Genkit\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. What Makes Genkit Stand Out\\n          \\n        1. Flows — Composable, Typed Pipelines\\n        2. Agent Abstractions\\n        3. The Dev UI — Where Genkit Truly Shines\\n        4. Broad Model Support — Provider Neutral by Design\\n        5. Pros and Cons\\n3. Vercel AI SDK\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. What Makes the Vercel AI SDK Stand Out\\n          \\n        1. Structured Generation and Agent Patterns\\n        2. Genkit vs.\\nVercel AI SDK — Abstraction Levels\\n        3. Pros and Cons\\n4. Mastra\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. What Makes Mastra Stand Out\\n          \\n        1. Workflows\\n        2. Pros and Cons\\n5. LangChain\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. LangChain’s Position: Agent-First, Platform-Tied\\n          \\n        1. LangSmith Observability\\n        2. Pros and Cons\\n6. Google ADK (Agent Development Kit)\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. ADK’s Position: Agent-First, Enterprise-Grade\\n          \\n        1. Multi-Agent Systems\\n        2. Vertex AI Lock-In\\n        3. Pros and Cons\\n7. Head-to-Head Comparison\\n   \\n    1. Developer Experience\\n    2. Abstraction Levels\\n    3. Observability\\n    4. Language Support\\n    5. Framework Neutrality\\n    6. Idiom and Code Style\\n8. Which Framework Should You Choose?\\n9. Conclusion\\n\\n## Introduction\\n\\nThe Generative AI tooling ecosystem has exploded over the past two years.\\nWhat started as a handful of Python libraries has grown into a rich, opinionated landscape of frameworks spanning multiple languages, deployment targets, and philosophy bets. As a developer who has shipped production applications using all five of the frameworks covered in this article, **Genkit** , **Vercel AI SDK** , **Mastra** , **LangChain** , and **Google ADK** , I want to offer a practical, hands-on view of where each one excels, where each one falls short, and what I would reach for depending on the project I’m building.\\n\\nThis is not a benchmark post. Tokens per second and latency numbers go stale within weeks. Instead, this is a developer experience and architecture comparison, the kind of thing that matters when you’re deciding what framework will carry your product through 2026 and beyond.\\n\\nA quick note on scope: all five frameworks are in active development and moving fast. Code samples in this article use the APIs as of **April 2026** .\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Genkit\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"103d77739048f6db\\\">>>\",\n      \"siteName\": \"xavidop.me\",\n      \"published\": \"2026-05-06\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"103d77739048f6db\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nJump to:\\n\\nNavigation\\n\\n* home\\n* / genkit\\n* / 2026-04-16-top-jsts-genai-frameworks-2026\\n\\n# Top JavaScript/TypeScript Gen AI Frameworks for 2026: A Hands-On Comparison\\n\\n16 Apr 2026 in Genkit on Genkit Last modified at: 2026-05-06\\n\\nTop JavaScript/TypeScript Gen AI Frameworks for 2026: A Hands-On Comparison\\n\\nA practical, in-depth comparison of the top Generative AI frameworks in 2026: Genkit, Vercel AI SDK, Mastra, LangChain, and Google ADK, from someone who has built with all of them. (English)\\n\\n1. Introduction\\n2. Genkit\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. What Makes Genkit Stand Out\\n          \\n        1. Flows — Composable, Typed Pipelines\\n        2. Agent Abstractions\\n        3. The Dev UI — Where Genkit Truly Shines\\n        4. Broad Model Support — Provider Neutral by Design\\n        5. Pros and Cons\\n3. Vercel AI SDK\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. What Makes the Vercel AI SDK Stand Out\\n          \\n        1. Structured Generation and Agent Patterns\\n        2. Genkit vs.\\nVercel AI SDK — Abstraction Levels\\n        3. Pros and Cons\\n4. Mastra\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. What Makes Mastra Stand Out\\n          \\n        1. Workflows\\n        2. Pros and Cons\\n5. LangChain\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. LangChain’s Position: Agent-First, Platform-Tied\\n          \\n        1. LangSmith Observability\\n        2. Pros and Cons\\n6. Google ADK (Agent Development Kit)\\n   \\n    1. History and Direction\\n    2. ADK’s Position: Agent-First, Enterprise-Grade\\n          \\n        1. Multi-Agent Systems\\n        2. Vertex AI Lock-In\\n        3. Pros and Cons\\n7. Head-to-Head Comparison\\n   \\n    1. Developer Experience\\n    2. Abstraction Levels\\n    3. Observability\\n    4. Language Support\\n    5. Framework Neutrality\\n    6. Idiom and Code Style\\n8. Which Framework Should You Choose?\\n9. Conclusion\\n\\n## Introduction\\n\\nThe Generative AI tooling ecosystem has exploded over the past two years.\\nWhat started as a handful of Python libraries has grown into a rich, opinionated landscape of frameworks spanning multiple languages, deployment targets, and philosophy bets. As a developer who has shipped production applications using all five of the frameworks covered in this article, **Genkit** , **Vercel AI SDK** , **Mastra** , **LangChain** , and **Google ADK** , I want to offer a practical, hands-on view of where each one excels, where each one falls short, and what I would reach for depending on the project I’m building.\\n\\nThis is not a benchmark post. Tokens per second and latency numbers go stale within weeks. Instead, this is a developer experience and architecture comparison, the kind of thing that matters when you’re deciding what framework will carry your product through 2026 and beyond.\\n\\nA quick note on scope: all five frameworks are in active development and moving fast. Code samples in this article use the APIs as of **April 2026** .\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n## Genkit\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"103d77739048f6db\\\">>>\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"6a4f54eedfc50f2d\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nTypeScript AI SDKs Rise in 2026: Framework Guide\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"6a4f54eedfc50f2d\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://marioottmann.com/articles/typescript-ai-sdks-rise-2026\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e86e36f0491b49f5\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nMario Ottmann\\n\\nArticles Newsletter Presentations [Work with me](https://withGravitas.de)\\n\\nDECEMBER 5, 2025\\n\\n# Why TypeScript-Based AI SDKs Are Reshaping Development in 2026\\n\\ntl;dr\\n\\nTypeScript-based AI SDKs are becoming viable alternatives to Python frameworks in 2026, driven by developers seeking unified tech stacks. While Python remains dominant for computationally intensive tasks, TypeScript frameworks like Mastra excel at orchestration, user-facing AI features, and seamless integration with modern web stacks.\\n\\nThe AI development landscape is undergoing a significant shift. For years, Python has dominated AI SDK adoption through frameworks like LangChain and CrewAI, largely because no competitive TypeScript alternatives existed. However, 2026 marks a turning point as non-technical entrepreneurs and solopreneurs increasingly prioritize unified development stacks over specialized, fragmented solutions.\\nThis evolution reflects a broader trend: developers want to build AI-powered features as native components of their applications, not isolated systems requiring separate environments, deployment pipelines, and expertise. This article was inspired by real-world experiences navigating this transition. Here's the LinkedIn post that sparked this comprehensive guide:\\n\\n## What Are TypeScript-Based AI SDKs?\\n\\nTypeScript-based AI SDKs are development frameworks that enable building AI-powered applications using TypeScript, JavaScript's statically-typed superset. Unlike traditional Python-centric AI tools, these SDKs integrate natively with modern web development stacks (React, Next.js, Node.js), allowing developers to build AI features using the same language and toolchain as their frontend and backend code. This unified approach eliminates context-switching and simplifies deployment architectures.\\nThese frameworks provide type-safe interfaces for interacting with large language models (LLMs), vector databases, agent orchestration systems, and other AI infrastructure. They're designed for developers who prioritize rapid iteration, seamless integration, and developer experience over raw computational performance.\\n\\n### The Historical Context: Python's Dominance\\n\\nPython became the default choice for AI development for legitimate reasons:\\n\\n* **Rich ecosystem** : Mature libraries like NumPy, pandas, and scikit-learn\\n* **Academic adoption** : Most AI research published with Python implementations\\n* **Framework maturity** : Early frameworks like LangChain and Crew AI launched Python-first\\n* **Community momentum** : Largest concentration of AI practitioners and resources\\n\\nHowever, this dominance created friction for web developers building AI-powered applications.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e86e36f0491b49f5\\\">>>\",\n      \"siteName\": \"marioottmann.com\",\n      \"published\": \"2025-12-05\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e86e36f0491b49f5\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nMario Ottmann\\n\\nArticles Newsletter Presentations [Work with me](https://withGravitas.de)\\n\\nDECEMBER 5, 2025\\n\\n# Why TypeScript-Based AI SDKs Are Reshaping Development in 2026\\n\\ntl;dr\\n\\nTypeScript-based AI SDKs are becoming viable alternatives to Python frameworks in 2026, driven by developers seeking unified tech stacks. While Python remains dominant for computationally intensive tasks, TypeScript frameworks like Mastra excel at orchestration, user-facing AI features, and seamless integration with modern web stacks.\\n\\nThe AI development landscape is undergoing a significant shift. For years, Python has dominated AI SDK adoption through frameworks like LangChain and CrewAI, largely because no competitive TypeScript alternatives existed. However, 2026 marks a turning point as non-technical entrepreneurs and solopreneurs increasingly prioritize unified development stacks over specialized, fragmented solutions.\\nThis evolution reflects a broader trend: developers want to build AI-powered features as native components of their applications, not isolated systems requiring separate environments, deployment pipelines, and expertise. This article was inspired by real-world experiences navigating this transition. Here's the LinkedIn post that sparked this comprehensive guide:\\n\\n## What Are TypeScript-Based AI SDKs?\\n\\nTypeScript-based AI SDKs are development frameworks that enable building AI-powered applications using TypeScript, JavaScript's statically-typed superset. Unlike traditional Python-centric AI tools, these SDKs integrate natively with modern web development stacks (React, Next.js, Node.js), allowing developers to build AI features using the same language and toolchain as their frontend and backend code. This unified approach eliminates context-switching and simplifies deployment architectures.\\nThese frameworks provide type-safe interfaces for interacting with large language models (LLMs), vector databases, agent orchestration systems, and other AI infrastructure. They're designed for developers who prioritize rapid iteration, seamless integration, and developer experience over raw computational performance.\\n\\n### The Historical Context: Python's Dominance\\n\\nPython became the default choice for AI development for legitimate reasons:\\n\\n* **Rich ecosystem** : Mature libraries like NumPy, pandas, and scikit-learn\\n* **Academic adoption** : Most AI research published with Python implementations\\n* **Framework maturity** : Early frameworks like LangChain and Crew AI launched Python-first\\n* **Community momentum** : Largest concentration of AI practitioners and resources\\n\\nHowever, this dominance created friction for web developers building AI-powered applications.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e86e36f0491b49f5\\\">>>\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"7dac898f59418c1a\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nFrontend Development Trends 2026: AI, Edge & TypeScript\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"7dac898f59418c1a\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://talent500.com/blog/frontend-development-trends-2026/\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b7cabe46dad6aaf9\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nDiscover the key trends that will shape frontend development in 2026, from AI-first workflows and meta-frameworks to edge computing, TypeScript, and modern frontend architecture.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b7cabe46dad6aaf9\\\">>>\",\n      \"siteName\": \"talent500.com\",\n      \"published\": \"2026-01-23\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b7cabe46dad6aaf9\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nDiscover the key trends that will shape frontend development in 2026, from AI-first workflows and meta-frameworks to edge computing, TypeScript, and modern frontend architecture.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b7cabe46dad6aaf9\\\">>>\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"4c56e5215eb944d3\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nTop JavaScript/TypeScript Gen AI Frameworks for 2026: A Hands ...\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"4c56e5215eb944d3\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://dev.to/gde/top-javascripttypescript-gen-ai-frameworks-for-2026-a-hands-on-comparisondescription-1g7\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"7e098a3963afb103\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nThe Generative AI framework landscape in 2026 is not a winner-take-all market. Each of the five frameworks covered here has a legitimate use case, a growing community, and an active development team.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"7e098a3963afb103\\\">>>\",\n      \"siteName\": \"dev.to\",\n      \"published\": \"2026-05-05\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"7e098a3963afb103\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nThe Generative AI framework landscape in 2026 is not a winner-take-all market. Each of the five frameworks covered here has a legitimate use case, a growing community, and an active development team.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"7e098a3963afb103\\\">>>\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"579bdb8948f2f70c\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nTypeScript Agent Frameworks in 2026: Loop, Runtime, Sandbox - DEV Community\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"579bdb8948f2f70c\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://dev.to/joeseifi/typescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm\",\n      \"description\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"825f431ff53a6af5\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n[Powered by Algolia](https://www.algolia.com/developers/?utm_source=devto&utm_medium=referral)\\n\\n \\n\\n## DEV Community\\n\\nAdd reaction\\n\\nLike Unicorn Exploding Head Raised Hands Fire\\n\\nJump to Comments Save Boost\\n\\nCopy link\\n\\nCopied to Clipboard\\n\\n[Share to X](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=%22TypeScript%20Agent%20Frameworks%20in%202026%3A%20Loop%2C%20Runtime%2C%20Sandbox%22%20by%20%40joeseifi%20%23DEVCommunity%20https%3A%2F%2Fdev.to%2Fjoeseifi%2Ftypescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm) [Share to LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&url=https%3A%2F%2Fdev.to%2Fjoeseifi%2Ftypescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm&title=TypeScript%20Agent%20Frameworks%20in%202026%3A%20Loop%2C%20Runtime%2C%20Sandbox&summary=A%20working%20senior%20engineer%27s%20map%20of%20TypeScript%20AI%20agent%20frameworks%20across%20three%20layers%20%E2%80%94%20the%20loop%2C%20the%20runtime%2C%20and%20the%20sandbox.%20Most%20teams%20need%20none%20of%20them.\\n&source=DEV%20Community) [Share to Facebook](https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fdev.to%2Fjoeseifi%2Ftypescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm) [Share to Mastodon](https://s2f.kytta.dev/?text=https%3A%2F%2Fdev.to%2Fjoeseifi%2Ftypescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm)\\n\\nReport Abuse\\n\\n[](https://media2.dev.to/dynamic/image/width=1000,height=420,fit=cover,gravity=auto,format=auto/https%3A%2F%2Fdev-to-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fuploads%2Farticles%2F49n2hz3zsxd3vsakf2r1.png)\\n\\nJoe Seifi\\n\\nPosted on May 3 • Originally published at [everydev.ai](https://everydev.ai/p/blog-typescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox)\\n\\n# TypeScript Agent Frameworks in 2026: Loop, Runtime, Sandbox\\n\\n\\\\# typescript \\\\# ai \\\\# agents \\\\# frameworks\\n\\n[](https://media2.dev.to/dynamic/image/width=800%2Cheight=%2Cfit=scale-down%2Cgravity=auto%2Cformat=auto/https%3A%2F%2Fdev-to-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fuploads%2Farticles%2F49n2hz3zsxd3vsakf2r1.png)\\nMost TypeScript teams shopping for an agent framework don't need one. A single `generateObject` call covers classification, extraction, summarization, tagging — the 80% case for production LLM work in TS right now.\\n\\nBut once the model starts deciding what to do next, surviving deploys, or coordinating with other agents, you start shopping. And the moment you do, you discover the TS agent ecosystem is not one market but three.\\n\\n##  Three layers\\n\\n**Loop** — wraps the agent loop so you don't write `while (!done) {…}` yourself. \\\"Let the model decide what to do next.\\\"\\n\\nMastra, Vercel AI SDK, Claude Agent SDK, OpenAI Agents SDK, LangGraph, AgentKit, VoltAgent, Google ADK.\\n\\n**Runtime** — keeps the loop alive across crashes, deploys, and long pauses. \\\"Keep the work alive when servers die.\\\"\\n\\nMastra Platform, LangGraph Platform, Claude Managed Agents, Inngest, Flue.\\n\\n**Sandbox** — runs an existing coding agent in isolation, often in parallel. \\\"Run ten Claude Codes in ten boxes.\\\"\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"825f431ff53a6af5\\\">>>\",\n      \"siteName\": \"dev.to\",\n      \"published\": \"2026-05-03\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"825f431ff53a6af5\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n[Powered by Algolia](https://www.algolia.com/developers/?utm_source=devto&utm_medium=referral)\\n\\n \\n\\n## DEV Community\\n\\nAdd reaction\\n\\nLike Unicorn Exploding Head Raised Hands Fire\\n\\nJump to Comments Save Boost\\n\\nCopy link\\n\\nCopied to Clipboard\\n\\n[Share to X](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=%22TypeScript%20Agent%20Frameworks%20in%202026%3A%20Loop%2C%20Runtime%2C%20Sandbox%22%20by%20%40joeseifi%20%23DEVCommunity%20https%3A%2F%2Fdev.to%2Fjoeseifi%2Ftypescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm) [Share to LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&url=https%3A%2F%2Fdev.to%2Fjoeseifi%2Ftypescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm&title=TypeScript%20Agent%20Frameworks%20in%202026%3A%20Loop%2C%20Runtime%2C%20Sandbox&summary=A%20working%20senior%20engineer%27s%20map%20of%20TypeScript%20AI%20agent%20frameworks%20across%20three%20layers%20%E2%80%94%20the%20loop%2C%20the%20runtime%2C%20and%20the%20sandbox.%20Most%20teams%20need%20none%20of%20them.\\n&source=DEV%20Community) [Share to Facebook](https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fdev.to%2Fjoeseifi%2Ftypescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm) [Share to Mastodon](https://s2f.kytta.dev/?text=https%3A%2F%2Fdev.to%2Fjoeseifi%2Ftypescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox-2flm)\\n\\nReport Abuse\\n\\n[](https://media2.dev.to/dynamic/image/width=1000,height=420,fit=cover,gravity=auto,format=auto/https%3A%2F%2Fdev-to-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fuploads%2Farticles%2F49n2hz3zsxd3vsakf2r1.png)\\n\\nJoe Seifi\\n\\nPosted on May 3 • Originally published at [everydev.ai](https://everydev.ai/p/blog-typescript-agent-frameworks-in-2026-loop-runtime-sandbox)\\n\\n# TypeScript Agent Frameworks in 2026: Loop, Runtime, Sandbox\\n\\n\\\\# typescript \\\\# ai \\\\# agents \\\\# frameworks\\n\\n[](https://media2.dev.to/dynamic/image/width=800%2Cheight=%2Cfit=scale-down%2Cgravity=auto%2Cformat=auto/https%3A%2F%2Fdev-to-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fuploads%2Farticles%2F49n2hz3zsxd3vsakf2r1.png)\\nMost TypeScript teams shopping for an agent framework don't need one. A single `generateObject` call covers classification, extraction, summarization, tagging — the 80% case for production LLM work in TS right now.\\n\\nBut once the model starts deciding what to do next, surviving deploys, or coordinating with other agents, you start shopping. And the moment you do, you discover the TS agent ecosystem is not one market but three.\\n\\n##  Three layers\\n\\n**Loop** — wraps the agent loop so you don't write `while (!done) {…}` yourself. \\\"Let the model decide what to do next.\\\"\\n\\nMastra, Vercel AI SDK, Claude Agent SDK, OpenAI Agents SDK, LangGraph, AgentKit, VoltAgent, Google ADK.\\n\\n**Runtime** — keeps the loop alive across crashes, deploys, and long pauses. \\\"Keep the work alive when servers die.\\\"\\n\\nMastra Platform, LangGraph Platform, Claude Managed Agents, Inngest, Flue.\\n\\n**Sandbox** — runs an existing coding agent in isolation, often in parallel. \\\"Run ten Claude Codes in ten boxes.\\\"\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"825f431ff53a6af5\\\">>>\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"searchId\": \"search_9a2dec32cb09475094600643c52ab62f\",\n  \"sessionId\": \"a41f975a-4880-459f-ab8f-7001c9813408\",\n  \"usage\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"sku_search\",\n      \"count\": 1\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"persistedDetailsTruncated":true,"originalDetailsBytesAtLeast":8193,"originalDetailKeys":["searchQueries","provider","count","tookMs","externalContent","results","searchId","sessionId","usage"],"sessionId":"a41f975a-4880-459f-ab8f-7001c9813408"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781712111325}}
